 :tx/rationale "HONEST ASSESSMENT: DW0-DW6 is the RIGHT fix for TODAY (1-10 concurrent agents) but NOT for the long-term vision (hundreds of agents). The three scaling ceilings are: (1) Single-threaded daemon — needs RwLock<Store> multi-threaded dispatch. (2) Per-txn .edn files — needs WAL for O(1) write + O(1) enumerate. (3) store.bin cache coherence — eliminated by daemon-as-live-index, but needs WAL for crash recovery. The question for the user: should we (A) ship DW0-DW6 now and add the scaling architecture later, or (B) design the WAL + multi-threaded daemon upfront and implement it all at once? Argument for A: DW0-DW6 fixes the immediate pain (stale cache) with ~850 LOC. The scaling work is ~5000+ LOC (WAL parser, checkpoint system, multi-threaded daemon, async dispatch). Shipping A first gets correctness NOW while designing B. Argument for B: If we build DW0-DW6 on the current file-per-txn architecture and then migrate to WAL later, we'll have to redo the marshal/routing work because the daemon internals change. Building B first avoids throwaway work. MY RECOMMENDATION: Ship DW0+DW0b immediately (~50 LOC, fixes the stale cache in all modes). Then design the WAL + multi-threaded daemon as a single coherent epic. DW1-DW4 (marshaling + routing) are still correct for B — the CLI→daemon routing is the same regardless of the daemon's internal architecture. DW5 (single LiveStore in direct mode) becomes less critical if the WAL handles concurrent direct-mode writers."
